bit on, a
Homonym Number:
Word Class: phrase
Sense Number:
Definition:(that's) a bit on, from the longer expressions on the cuff (q.v.) <i>nose</i>, the <i>snorer,</i> that's tough; that's a bit much; see also cuff.
Origin: [none]
Register:
Register 2:
Domain: [none]
Region: [none]
See:
Pronunciation:
Notes: ca1945 e.g's `I want four pounds for it.' `Gee, that's a bit on' `He got three years hard for bookying.' `That was a bit on, wasn't it?'; also meaning 'rather drunk' in citation below
Citations
Date:  0/0/1939
Source:  First White Boy Born in Otago
Author:  BEATTIE
Vol / Page:  178
Edition:
Quote:  The doctor came to the north bank and left his horse, and he and [Jimmy] the Needle double-banked across. The Needle was washed off and the doctor rode to the hut. He must have been `a bit on' to leave the other in the river. ... he was asked `Where's the Needle?' He replied `In Hell!'
